      "output": "Title: How to Resolve Blue Screen Error with ...\nURL: https://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/support/articles/000028099/processors/intel-core-processors.html\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIf you receive a blue screen error (also known as a stop code) with WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR, it means that a hardware issue has occurred on your computer.\n\n---\n\nTitle: How to fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR - Microsoft Support\nURL: https://support.microsoft.com/en-gb/windows/how-to-fix-whea-uncorrectable-error-7c49d78a-2792-96cf-2268-abbe9d9eb29f\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nHow to fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR - Microsoft Support\n...\nWhen a hardware error occurs on a Windows device, it shuts down suddenly and might display a blue screen/stop error with the following error message:\n...\nWHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR\n...\nTo attempt to fix this issue, try the actions from the following list:\n...\n## Use Windows Update to receive the latest updates and drivers\n...\nUse Windows Update to receive the latest updates and drivers. For more information on how to use Windows Update to receive the latest updates and drivers, see the following article:\n...\n## Manually update drivers\n...\nIf the blue screen/stop error gives an indication of which hardware device is causing the issue, the drivers for the hardware device causing the issue can be manually updated. For more information, see the following article:\n...\nImportant: Microsoft recommends trying to first automatically update drivers using Windows Update. For more information, see the article Automatically get recommended drivers and updates for your hardware.\n...\n## Use System Restore or Startup Repair\n...\nUse one of the Windows options to restore or repair Windows. This option is the best option when a recent change was done to the Windows device that could be causing the issue, for example:\n...\nMicrosoft updates were installed.\n...\nAn updated driver was installed.\n...\nA new app was installed.\n...\nFor more information, see the following article:\n...\n## Troubleshoot the blue screen/stop error\n...\nUse the following article to perform further troubleshooting on the blue screen/stop error:\n...\nResolving Blue Screen errors in Windows\n\n---\n\nTitle: How to fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR\nURL: https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/how-to-fix-whea-uncorrectable-error-7c49d78a-2792-96cf-2268-abbe9d9eb29f?linkId=183209200\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nUNCORRECTABLE\n...\nIf you receive a blue screen error (also known as a stop code), it means that your PC has shut down suddenly to protect itself from data loss. If you see the text “WHEA\\_UNCORRECTABLE\\_ERROR,” it means that a hardware error has occurred. To fix it, try the following:\n...\n* Get all the latest updates with Windows Update. Go to**Start**>**Settings**>**Windows Update**, and then select**Check for updates**.\n...\n* Try[restoring Windows back to an earlier point in time.](https://support.microsoft.com/help/12415/)\n...\n[Check for Windows updates](ms-settings:windowsupdate)\n...\n* Get all the latest updates with Windows Update. Go to**Start**>**Settings**>**Update & security**>**Windows Update**, and then select**Check for updates**.\n* Try[restoring Windows back to an earlier point in time.](https://support.microsoft.com/help/12415/)\n...\n[Check for Windows updates](ms-settings:windowsupdate)\n\n---\n\nTitle: Fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR on Windows 11 | RebootDoctor\nURL: https://rebootdoctor.com/blog/whea-uncorrectable-error-windows-11/\nPublished: 2026-05-27T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nShort answer: WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR (0x00000124) is one of the few BSODs that genuinely means hardware — the CPU reported an error it could not self-correct. Check Event Viewer under WHEA-Logger for the source. Common culprits are unstable overclocks or XMP/EXPO memory profiles (disable them first), an overheating CPU, a failing PSU, or on Intel 13th/14th-gen chips the known voltage degradation.\n...\nWHEA stands for Windows Hardware Error Architecture. When you see this blue screen, the CPU itself reported a hardware error that it couldn’t correct on its own. Stop code 0x00000124. This is one of the few BSODs that genuinely means hardware — not a driver crash, not a software bug, not a corrupted file. The processor’s error-correcting hardware detected something wrong with either the CPU, the motherboard’s voltage regulation, or the memory bus, and it couldn’t self-correct. Windows had no choice but to crash.\n...\nIf you’re overclocking — CPU, RAM with XMP/EXPO, GPU — this is the crash that tells you to stop. An unstable overclock is the single most common trigger for WHEA errors on otherwise healthy hardware. The CPU is running at a voltage or frequency it can’t reliably sustain, and the error correction catches it.\n...\nDisable XMP in BIOS first. If the crashes stop, XMP was pushing the memory controller past what your particular CPU can handle. Try the default 2133 MHz (DDR4) or 4800 MHz (DDR5) for a week. If stable, re-enable XMP at a lower speed — step down one tier at a time until you find what’s stable.\n...\nInstall HWiNFO and check if thermal throttling or abnormal voltages precede the crashes. CPU hitting 100°C? The overheating is the real problem and WHEA is the symptom. VCore fluctuating wildly under load? PSU or VRM issue.\n...\nThe CPU itself detected a hardware error it couldn't self-correct. WHEA stands for Windows Hardware Error Architecture. Unlike most blue screens caused by driver bugs, this one genuinely points at hardware — the processor, motherboard voltage regulators, or PCIe bus reported a fault that Windows couldn't recover from.\n...\nAlmost always. The most common exception is an unstable overclock — XMP memory profiles, CPU overclocks, or motherboard auto-overclock features pushing components past their stable limit. Reset everything to stock first. If WHEA errors continue at stock settings with no overclocking, it's genuine hardware failure.\n...\nOpen Event Viewer, Windows Logs, System, filter for WHEA-Logger events. The Error Source field tells you: Machine Check Exception means CPU. PCIe Bus Error means GPU, NVMe, or slot issue. If the same CPU core is named in every crash, the CPU die has a defect — contact the manufacturer for warranty replacement.\n\n---\n\nTitle: How to Fix “WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR” on Windows 11 - Guiding Tech\nURL: https://www.guidingtech.com/fix-whea-uncorrectable-error-windows-10-11/\nPublished: 2024-02-09T13:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: Abhishek Mishra\nHighlights:\n## What Is the ‘WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR’ BSOD Issue?\n...\nThe ‘WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR’ is a BSOD (Blue Screen of Death) issue that usually indicates a hardware problem on your Windows 11 PC. It may arise due to one of the following reasons:\n...\n- Corrupt or outdated device drivers.\n- A hardware component failure.\n- Bad or corrupted system memory (DRAM).\n- Overheated system components.\n- Software conflicts.\n- A buggy Windows Update.\n...\n## Basic Fixes\n...\n- Update all device drivers: Obsolete device drivers on Windows 11 can result in the ‘WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR’ BSOD issue. Open the Device Manager app and expand all device entries to look for a yellow warning sign. Right-click the problematic device and select Update driver.\n...\n- Avoid using the system when overheating: Overheating system components can cause BSOD errors. Wait patiently and use the system when it cools down.\n...\n- Remove overclocking system components: Overclocking various system components leads to erratic temperature spikes. You must remove overclocking the system components (RAM, CPU, or GPU), and reboot the PC.\n...\n- Update Windows 11: Press the Windows + I shortcut to open Settings, select Windows Update from the sidebar, and install available system updates.\n...\n## Fix 1: Run a Check Disk Scan\n...\nDisk errors such as bad or missing sectors are a common reason behind BSOD issues on Windows 11. Run the Check Disk utility to scan and repair them.\n...\n## Fix 2: Check RAM With Memory Diagnostic Utility\n...\nIf the Check Disk scan doesn’t find any errors, you must inspect the system memory for issues (e.g. corrupt memory, DRAM). Windows 11 offers a Memory Diagnostic Utility to check and resolve all RAM-related errors.\n...\nClick ‘Restart now\n...\ncheck for problems\n...\n## Fix 3: Use Event Viewer to Identify a Problematic Device\n...\nMicrosoft Windows offers an Event Viewer tool that contains a comprehensive log of all system events including errors and warnings. You can use it to locate the ‘WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR’ and find the underlying cause to fix it.\n...\nStep 3: Select the ‘WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR’ in the list to view the associated details such as the Vendor ID or PCI ID of the device reporting the issue. Once you’ve identified the problematic hardware (e.g. video card), try reconnecting or reseating it.\n...\n## Fix 4: Uninstall the Recent Windows Update\n...\nSometimes, a buggy Windows update can break existing PC features. If you’re getting a BSOD error after a recent Windows update installation, roll it back to restore normalcy.\n...\n## Fix 5: Reset BIOS Settings\n...\nIf you notice the ‘WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR’ on Windows after tweaking BIOS settings, you must revert them to their default state.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Fixing WHEA_uncorrectable_error on windows 10 - Microsoft Q&A\nURL: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/answers/questions/5507779/fixing-whea-uncorrectable-error-on-windows-10\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nUnfortunately, without more information, there is no way to know if this is truly a hardware issue and/or what it is. You'll need to get more information. The BSOD provides some basic information that is helpful that you could provide us. After you reboot then use Windows Search to find the`Reliability History` app. This shows a summary of application crashes and BSODs. If you look at the error related to the BSOD then it will contain more information that we can use to diagnose the problem.\n...\nIn a perfect world\n...\ncrash dump file that is automatically generated\n...\ncan be viewed to\n...\nnarrow down what is failing. But that would require analyzing in a debugger\n...\nproviding as much details\n...\nexact error code and\n...\nThat is helpful. The GenuineIntel.sys would seem to point toward a processor hardware failure. The 124 indicates a hardware failure.\n...\nI would probably start with ensuring the CPU is not overheating. Modern CPUs will throttle down as they heat up to prevent this. If you notice the system slowing down before the BSOD then that would seem to lead that way. I would recommend you use a tool like CoreTemp to monitor you CPU temps. If they are going too high then you have a heat problem.\n...\nIf this is an older machine and/or in a dusty place then open the case and ensure all the dust is blown out and then turn on the machine and ensure all the fans are spinning correctly as well. If any aren't working (especially the one on the CPU) then you'll need to replace them.\n...\nIf the system isn't under load then the temp are probably fine. That means your thermal paste is doing its job. It is when it goes under load that the temps can spike and crash the machine. A quick google indicates that 90 C or higher is not good.\n...\nAfter the dusting then monitor the temps while under\n...\nto do (\n...\nmyself) but\n...\nto see what\n...\ntemps were when it\n...\nPerhaps your temp monitoring tool can log information to disk so you can get back\n...\nIf it isn't temps or dust then a faulty processor (or connection to motherboard) could be the cause. I think a computer shop would need to look at that point.\n...\nThe WHEA error does indeed mean there's a hardware issue. I have posted some possible issues with possible fixes for you to try. However, bringing the PC to a professional to get looked at may be your best bet.\n...\n- This could be an issue with the RAM, CPU, hard drive or even overclocking. If you're using a desktop PC then double check the hardware connections including the CPU and RAM. Make sure that all connections are secure.\n- Driver updates can cause issues if they're too old. Try opening the Device Manager and check to see if there are any drivers that need updates.\n\n---\n\nTitle: How to Fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR in Windows 10/11 - Windows Mode\nURL: https://www.windowsmode.com/fix-whea-uncorrectable-error-windows/\nPublished: 2026-05-14T11:10:08.000Z\nAuthor: Adam LaFoute\nHighlights:\nGetting a WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR blue screen on Windows? This crash means Windows detected a hardware fault it could not recover from. Unlike most blue screens, this one points directly at your hardware or the drivers controlling it with a stop code of 0x00000124.\n...\nThis guide covers the most effective fixes in order from quickest to most thorough. Most people solve it by Fix 2 or Fix 3. If your PC is overclocked, start with Fix 1 first.\n...\n- Windows detected an unrecoverable hardware error and forced a restart.\n- Most common causes: overclocking, faulty RAM, bad device driver, or overheating CPU.\n- Less common causes: failing hard drive or SSD, corrupted system files, bad Windows update.\n- This is a hardware-level crash, not a typical app or software error.\n- Affects Windows 10 and Windows 11. More common on overclocked or custom-built PCs.\n...\nWork through these fixes in order. If your PC is overclocked, go straight to Fix 1 first. Otherwise start from the top and move down. Most people are done by Fix 3 or Fix 4.\n...\nA bad driver is one of the most common software-side causes of this error. GPU drivers are the most frequent offenders, but chipset, network,\n...\nstorage drivers can also trigger it\n...\nIf the crashes started\n...\n| Fix | Time Needed | Best If |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Disable overclocking / XMP | 5 – 10 min | PC is overclocked or XMP is enabled in BIOS |\n| Update or roll back drivers | 10 – 20 min | Error started after a driver update |\n| SFC and DISM scan | 15 – 30 min | Error appeared after a Windows update or crash |\n| RAM test (MemTest86) | 1 – 3 hours | Crashes happen randomly with no obvious trigger |\n| Check CPU temperature | 10 – 15 min | PC crashes under load (gaming, rendering) |\n| Check drive health | 10 – 20 min | PC is old, drive makes clicking sounds, or slow to boot |\n| Windows Update and BIOS update | 20 – 45 min | System is behind on updates or BIOS is very old |\n...\nhardware or drivers. Overclocking is the most common trigger. Faulty RAM, a failing drive, a corrupted device driver,\n...\na CPU running too hot can all cause it. In\n...\ncases a bad\n...\nupdate or driver conflict is the culprit, which\n...\nit fixable without\n...\nany hardware.\n...\nYes, and it is the single most common cause. If your CPU, RAM, or GPU is running above stock speeds, resetting everything to default is the first thing to try. Even a “stable” overclock can become unstable after a Windows update or temperature change.\n...\nIn most cases, yes. Disabling overclocking, updating or rolling back drivers, running SFC and DISM, and testing RAM resolves the error for the majority of users. A Windows reinstall is only needed if system files are deeply corrupted and no other fix works.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Resolving the WHEA uncorrectable error in Windows 10\nURL: https://www.manageengine.com/products/eventlog/kb/resolving-whea-uncorrectable-error-windows-10.html\nPublished: 2024-11-25T08:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: ManageEngine\nHighlights:\nThe Windows Hardware Error Architecture (WHEA) uncorrectable error is a blue screen of death (BSOD) issue caused by hardware-related malfunctions.",
